The main idea of most of these overloads is to separate mappings from iterables. IMO this is needed if we want to type the iteratees properly. `Iterable` is not a `Mapping` and `Mapping` is an `Iterable` but it is not generic on the value of the mapping.

```python
@t.overload
def sort_by(
    collection: t.Mapping[t.Any, T2],
    iteratee: t.Union[t.Callable[[T2], t.Any], IterateeObjT, None] = None,
    reverse: bool = False,
) -> t.List[T2]:
    ...


@t.overload
def sort_by(
    collection: t.Iterable[T],
    iteratee: t.Union[t.Callable[[T], t.Any], IterateeObjT, None] = None,
    reverse: bool = False,
) -> t.List[T]:
    ...
```
So the idea here is that without overload we have no way to say this function accepts any iterable and the iteratee's first argument (if it is a callable) will be the value of the mapping if we use a mapping as `collection`

This is because pydash passes the value of the mapping as first argument to the iteratee which is nice but it makes typing a bit trickier.

