@samuelcolvin I'm changing it to `model_concrete_name` for now, but one other alternative I'd like to propose: for public methods, using `model__` as a prefix, rather than `model_` (so `model__concrete_name` instead of `model_concrete_name`; similarly `model__json`, etc.).

This feels significantly less likely to run into collisions with user-desired fields (or methods), and to my eye almost *more* readable (as I can immediately tell it is a pydantic model method, since nothing else uses a format like that), with only one extra character. And it retains the various benefits of the method name being pseudo-public (e.g., IDEs including it at the top of autocomplete, etc.).

If you consider this an already-finalized decision, or just hate this proposal, let's just pretend this comment never happened :).

